<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n14232a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14232a">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14232a"> 232(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> baptise armies / bapt. RC &amp; Norse / Thor&apos;s hammer</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Many Norwegians remained pagan at the close of the 11th century, refusing to submit even to the nominal Christianity then required, districts and <mark>armies being baptized</mark> without any instruction whatsoever. The <mark>forms of pagans and Christians</mark> were in some respects similar, pouring water over the head and giving a name, being ceremonies of Odinism; &ldquo;<mark>Thor&apos;s hammersign</mark>&rdquo; being used like that of the cross (and sometimes mistaken for it) in religious rites and blessings. <small> Charles Haliday, <a name="SKD1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SKD1"><cite title="source">The Scandinavian Kingdom of Dublin</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (1884) 125</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
